Drug patent: 20 years
Generic drug: non-proprietary, after patent expiration
Drug development: research and registration, ~10 years
Research phases
- preclinical: non-human subjects
- phase I: 20-100 subjects, test safety
- phase II: 100-300 subjects, test efficacy and side effects
- phase III: 300-3000 subjects, test effectiveness
Registration: FDA in USA, EMA in EU

#Asparaginase
enzyme breaking down asparagine
used to tread lymphoblastic leukemia, many side effects

#Amphetamine
CNS stimulant, improves congnitive control
recreational drug, addictive

#Barbiturates
depressant, general anesthesia

#Benzodiazepines
depressant

#Xanthines
Caffeine: CNS stimulant
Theobromine

#Lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD)
psychedelic, hallucinations
recreational drug

#Benzocaine
local anesthetic
blocks sodium channels on neuron membrane

#Lidocaine
local anesthetic
blocks sodium channels on neuron membrane

#Artemisinin
contains peroxide ring
treatment of malaria and parasitic worms

#Antibiotics
Penicillin: inhibits cell wall synthesis
Cephalosporin: inhibits cell wall synthesis
Erythromycin: inhibits protein synthesis
Streptomycin: inhibits protein synthesis
Tetracycline: inhibits protein synthesis

#Analgesics: pain relievers
Morphine: recreational drug, found in opium, addictive
Codeine: prodrug of morphine, found in opium
Heroin: recreational drug, addictive
Fentanyl: very strong, addictive

#Vaccines: activate acquired immunity
Attenuated: contain weakened live pathogen
Inactivated: contain destroyed pathogen
Subunit: contain fragments of pathogen
Conjugate: combine weak and strong antigen
Heterotypic: similar pathogen of another animal (cowpox/smallpox)
Genetic
- viral: use safe virus to insert pathogen gene
- mRNA: RNA packaged in nanoparticles
- DNA
Experimental
- dendritic cell
- recombinant
Mandatory/recommended
- rotavirus
- diphtheria
- tetanus
- pertussis
- hepatitis B
- haemophilus influenzae B
- pneumococcal (Prevnar)
- meningococcal
- polio
- measles
- mumps
- rubella
- varicella (Varivax)
Optional
- influenza
- corona (Comirnaty)
- HPV (Gardasil)
- tuberculosis
- encephalitis

Fialuridine: failed hepatitis B treatment, caused liver failure [1993]
Theralizumab (TGN1412): failed immunomodulator, caused organ failure [2006]

#Drugs
Humira: monoclonal antibody (autoimmune diseases)
Keytruda: humanized antibody (cancer)
Paxlovid: covid-19
Eliquis: anticoagulant
Eylea: macular edema
Biktarvy: HIV
Revlimid: myeloma
Stelara: monoclonal antibody
Dupixent: allergies
Imbruvica: leukemia
Opdivo: cancer
Darzalex: myeloma
Trikafta: cystic fibrosis
Xarelto: anticoagulant
Trulicity: diabetes

=ATC (Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical)
drug classification system

#A / Alimentary tract and metabolism
A02 / Antiacids
A03 / Anticholinergic
A03 / Antispasmodic: suppress muscle spasms
A04 / Antiemetic: against vomitting
- Setrons: block serotonin receptors in CNS and digestive system
A06 / Laxative
A07 / Antidiarrhoeal
A11 / Vitamins
A12 / Mineral supplements
A13 / Tonics
A14 / Anabolic steroids: mimic effects of testosterone

#B / Blood and blood forming organs
B01 / Antithrombotic: reduce blood cloths formation
B02 / Antihemorrhagic: stop bleeding
B03 / Antianemic

#C / Cardiovascular system
C02 / Antihypertensive: treat high blood pressure
C03 / Diuretic: increase urine production

#D / Dermatologicals
D01 / Antifungals
D02 / Emollients: moisture
D04 / Antipruritic: inhibit itching
D05 / Antipsoriatics
D08 / Antiseptics

#G / Genito-urinary system

#H / Systemic hormonal preparations

#J / Antiinfectives
J07 / Vaccines

#L / Antineoplastic and immunomodulating agents 

#M / Musculo-skeletal system

#N / Nervous system
N01 / Anesthetics
N02 / Analgesics
N03 / Antiepileptics (Anticonvulsants)
N05 / Psycholeptics: calming effect
N06 / Psychoanaleptics: CNS stimulants

#P / Antiparasitic products, insecticides and repellents

#R / Respiratory system
R06 / Antihistamines

#S / Sensory organs

#V / Various
V01 / Allergen: produce strong immune response
V08 / Contrast media
